  <header class="post-header">
    <h1>Commenting for Continuity: Why My Code Comments Don&#39;t Look Like Yours (On Purpose)</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      2025-10-27 ¬∑ ~7 min read
      
    </p>
    
    
    <ul class="tags-list">
      
      <li><a href="/tags/azure" class="tag-badge">azure</a></li>
      
      <li><a href="/tags/devops" class="tag-badge">devops</a></li>
      
      <li><a href="/tags/kql" class="tag-badge">kql</a></li>
      
      <li><a href="/tags/powershell" class="tag-badge">powershell</a></li>
      
      <li><a href="/tags/Terraform" class="tag-badge">Terraform</a></li>
      
      <li><a href="/tags/governance" class="tag-badge">governance</a></li>
      
    </ul>
    
    
    
      <p class="summary">Most guides say &#39;comment the why, not the what.&#39; Azure admins need more: comments that double as runbooks, audit trails, and change-board briefs.</p>
    
  </header>

  
  <p class="post-actions" style="margin:.5rem 0 0; text-align: center;">
    <button class="btn"
            onclick="window.print(); return false;"
            title="Print this page"
